t hold us back from imagining a postracist America? Or could the psychic hold of slavery be understood as a tool, helping us get a grip on the systemic racial inequalities and restricted liberties that persist in the present day? Featuring original essays from an array of established and emerging scholars in the interdisciplinary field of African American studies, The Psychic Hold of Slavery offers a nuanced dialogue upon these questions. With a painful awareness that our understanding of the past informs our understanding of the present—and vice versa—the contributors place slavery’s historical legacies in conversation with twenty-first-century manifestations of antiblack violence, dehumanization, and social death. Through an exploration of film, drama, fiction, performance art, graphic novels, and philosophical discourse, this volume considers how artists grapple with questions of representation, as they ask whether slavery can ever be accurately depicted, trace the scars that slavery has left on a traumatized body politic, or debate how to best convey that black lives matter. The Psychic Hold of Slavery thus raises provocative questions about how we behold the historically distinct event of African diasporic enslavement and how we might hold off the transhistorical force of antiblack domination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAfrican Americans in literature. 0aAfrican AmericansxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAvilez, GerShun.1 aAvilez, Gershun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaney, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChaney, Michael.1 aColbert, Soyica Diggs, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat